{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17584196","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17584196"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T07:41:58+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T07:41:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14430"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14430","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14430"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.75,0.03,0.05,0.05,0.13]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7125"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"60246"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7125","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7125"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14430"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"45666"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"29"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4906"},{"type":"tags","id":"4907"},{"type":"tags","id":"4926"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"6641"},{"type":"tags","id":"6642"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"17022"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17160"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"60246","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/60246"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following valvular abnormalities most commonly occurs as a long-term complication of rheumatic fever?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Mitral stenosis","Aortic regurgitation","Tricuspid regurgitation","Aortic stenosis","Mitral valve prolapse"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe valvular abnormality that most commonly occurs as a long-term complication of rheumatic fever is \u003Cstrong\u003Emitral stenosis\u003C/strong\u003E. Rheumatic fever, an inflammatory disease that can follow a group A streptococcal infection, often affects the heart valves, particularly the mitral valve. Therefore, urgent treatment of at risk individuals is key to prevent this long term complication of rheumatic fever. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe other options are less common or not typically associated with rheumatic fever:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAortic regurgitation\u003C/strong\u003E can occur in rheumatic fever but is less common than mitral stenosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETricuspid regurgitation\u003C/strong\u003E is rarely caused by rheumatic fever.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAortic stenosis\u003C/strong\u003E can be a complication of rheumatic fever but is less frequent than mitral stenosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMitral valve prolapse\u003C/strong\u003E is not typically associated with rheumatic fever and is more commonly a congenital or degenerative condition.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003ERheumatic fever can cause inflammation and scarring of the mitral valve leaflets, leading to their thickening and fusion. Over time, this results in narrowing of the mitral valve orifice, causing mitral stenosis. While other valvular abnormalities can occur, mitral stenosis remains the most common long-term valvular complication of rheumatic fever.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Rheumatic fever commonly affects the mitral valve, leading to various valvular abnormalities.","Mitral stenosis is the most common long-term valvular complication of rheumatic fever, while mitral valve prolapse is not typically associated with this condition."],"references":["Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. Robbins Basic Pathology (10th ed.). 2017. Elsevier - Health Sciences Division","Krapf L, Dreyfus J, Cueff C, Lepage L, Brochet E, Vahanian A, Messika-Zeitoun D. Anatomical features of rheumatic and non-rheumatic mitral stenosis: potential additional value of three-dimensional echocardiography. Arch Cardiovasc Dis. 2013 Feb;106(2):111-5. doi: 10.1016/j.acvd.2012.11.004. Epub 2013 Jan 23. PMID: 23527915.","Sika-Paotonu D, Beaton A, Raghu A, et al. Acute Rheumatic Fever and Rheumatic Heart Disease. 2017 Mar 10 [Updated 2017 Apr 3]. In: Ferretti JJ, Stevens DL, Fischetti VA, editors. Streptococcus pyogenes : Basic Biology to Clinical Manifestations [Internet]. Oklahoma City (OK): University of Oklahoma Health Sciences Center; 2016-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK425394/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"45666"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14430"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"45666","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/45666"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-10T13:28:26+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-10T13:28:50+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7125"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"60246"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"29","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/29"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2c","name":"Pathology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"4"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position